  "full_text_flowing_modernisation_text_block": "When the Imperial Visit occurs to one of the brilliant [mosques/sites], to His Royal Dust-Foot,\n[people] have started daring to present petitions. Although the Imperial grace and benevolence\nis limitless, and considering the Padishah's mercy and compassion it is impossible to prevent this;\nnevertheless, it is not worthy or appropriate to disturb the Royal Stirrup at all times, timely or untimely, even for trivial matters,\nespecially since the fortunate day of Friday is counted among the holidays of Muslims.\nOut of respect for the Possessor of Command (the Sultan), the presentation and expression of such petitions on the mentioned noble day\nto the Dust-Foot of the Imam of Muslims and Caliph of the Earth must be in accordance with the manners of servitude.\nBased on this, hereafter, apart from the Imperial Sultanate's Friday Selamlik procession,\nat times other than the Royal Visit, for whatever matter it may be,\none must avoid and abstain from presenting petitions to the Royal Dust-Foot. Those with needs\nand necessities should express and state their requests according to the principles of regulation and observed rules,\nto their officer or to the place they are affiliated with, regardless of which class or degree they belong to in that matter.\nThrough their [the officers'] mediation, the request will be granted and executed, and the affair\nwill be seen to and fulfilled. As for the destitute and helpless who have no connection to any degree or affiliation to any career path,\nfor the affairs that will arise, as described above,\nthey must beware and beware of presenting petitions to the Royal Imperial Stirrup on days other than Fridays.\nSince the matter has been notified to those concerned so that they do not do so, and so that it be known to all,\nit is inserted and printed in this place as well, so that no one dares to act to the contrary.\n\nCounted among the sovereign good intentions and the royal noble qualities, compassions, and favors of His Majesty Our Master\nthat manifest regarding the servants and the crowns of all the people of the lands;\nthis time, to the officials of the bureaus and the truthfulness-characterized servants of the Sublime Porte,\nand to some veteran servants who have chosen the corner of retirement and are in need of mercy and compassion,\nand to the helpless subjects whose houses were burnt in the fire that occurred recently in Beyoğlu and who were scattered and dispersed in places\nof narrowness and misery, an ample Royal Imperial gift was graciously bestowed and granted.\nFurthermore, from the chastity-honored high side of Her Highness the Illustrious and Chaste Valide Sultan of high glory,\nhigh zeal was deemed appropriate for the granting of a sufficient amount of beautiful gifts to all classes of\nthe Royal Regular and Naval soldiers found in Istanbul, and to the students of the School of Judicial Knowledge,\nwhich was invented and executed by the glorious efforts of His Excellency the Paradise-Dwelling Sovereign [Mahmud II].\n(Sentence continues from previous lines)\nThese imperial and beautiful gifts were distributed and divided class by class according to their ranks,\nand each of them attained their share of joy and hopes, becoming the object of the kindness and favor of the Padishah\nof praised qualities. The obligatory prayers for His Crowning Excellency, which they are diligent in,\nwere repeatedly raised to the Court of the Divine Helper. The ruined hearts and burns of the helpless people\nand subjects who were victims of the fire were extinguished by this fresh water of Royal benevolence and kindness,\nand they were made prosperous and flourishing anew.\n\nDuring the Imperial Era of the Glorious Crowning Father, His Excellency the Paradise-Abiding Sovereign,\nthe Honored Said Beg Efendi, who had been employed for a long period in the pride-requiring service of the Imperial Palace Secretariat,\nbeing a man of sagacity and seriousness, and one of the servants worthy of employment in the services of the Exalted State;\nbased on this, it was the High Desire that the aforesaid Bey attain a suitable service\nunder the majesty-abounding shadow of His Royal Excellency, as a reward for his service and labor.\nThe Governorship of the Imperial Gunpowder Works, which is within the Ministry of War Munitions,\nwhile administered by an independent official from old times,\nalthough lately united [with another office], since this official duty is principally among the great affairs\nand its administration by separation according to its previous principle appears to be an improvement,\npursuant to the Royal Imperial order and will issued on that matter due to these aspects,\nthe mentioned Gunpowder Works were separated from the Ministry of War Munitions and transferred\nand delegated to the aforesaid Bey.\n\nDue to the honorable occurrence of the auspicious Imperial Accession of His Crowning Excellency...",
  "summary": "This text from the Takvîm-i Vekâyi contains three distinct sections. First, it issues a strict royal decree regulating the presentation of petitions (`arz-ı hâl`) to the Sultan. It criticizes the public for disturbing the Sultan with trivial matters during his visits and processions, particularly on Fridays (a holy day). It mandates that petitions must now go through proper bureaucratic channels or officers, and direct petitions to the Sultan are forbidden except on Fridays during the Selamlik, and even then, only by the destitute. Second, it announces the distribution of royal monetary gifts (`atiyye`) from the Sultan and the Valide Sultan to government scribes, retired servants, victims of the recent Beyoğlu fire, and students, as an act of charity and benevolence. Third, it announces an administrative appointment: Said Beg Efendi, a former palace scribe, is appointed as the Governor of the Imperial Gunpowder Works (`Baruthane-i Amire`), which is being separated from the Ministry of War Munitions to be administered independently again."

